<!-- ===== SECURITY ===== -->
<section id="security" style="padding-top:80px;">
  <div class="sh">
    <div class="si-idx">02</div>
    <div>
      <div class="s-tag">Security Operations</div>
      <h2 class="s-title">Layered Security.<br>Production-Tuned Controls.</h2>
      <p class="s-desc">
        Security is operational discipline, not a configuration checklist. This environment
        handles high-volume traffic with edge protection and origin security controls
        filtered at the edge. WAF rules are derived from observed production traffic patterns, not generic templates.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="panel-grid g3">
    <div class="panel">
      <div class="p-badge">Edge Layer</div>
      <div class="p-title">Cloudflare WAF + Bot Management</div>
      <div class="p-body">
        Custom WAF expression rules targeting referer spam, L7 flood patterns, and
        credential stuffing. Rate limiting per IP and per path with burst allowances
        tuned to preserve legitimate crawler access. Bot Fight Mode and CAPTCHA challenges
        deployed selectively. Rules written from live attack data and progressively
        cleaned up after traffic normalizes. No permanent emergency state.
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="panel">
      <div class="p-badge">Origin Layer</div>
      <div class="p-title">ModSecurity OWASP CRS Tuning</div>
      <div class="p-body">
        OWASP CRS deployed on production NGINX hosts. Paranoia level calibrated per
        environment. Rule IDs adjusted for application-specific false positive patterns
        using <code style="color:var(--amber)">SecRuleRemoveById</code> scoped to
        affected URL paths, not globally disabled. CRS tuning applied in audit
        mode first, then enforcement, validated against captured production request samples.
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="panel">
      <div class="p-badge">AI Integration</div>
      <div class="p-title">AI-Assisted Ops &amp; Application Deployment</div>
      <div class="p-body">
        AI tooling integrated into the operations workflow for log pattern analysis,
        anomaly triage, and automation script generation. Experience deploying
        AI-backed applications, including Supabase-authenticated services with
        vector storage, API gateway integration, and user session management in
        containerized environments.
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="panel-grid g3" style="margin-top:3rem;">
    <div class="panel">
      <div class="p-badge">Kubernetes</div>
      <div class="p-title">Cluster controls and isolation</div>
      <div class="p-body">
        RBAC limits who can change what in the API. NetworkPolicies constrain pod-to-pod
        traffic so workloads cannot talk to everything by default. Admission controllers
        and policy enforce allowed images, labels, and security context before objects
        land in the cluster. Pod Security or restricted defaults keep privileged pods from
        becoming the norm. System components and platform services live in dedicated
        namespaces, separate from application workloads, so blast radius and change
        ownership stay clear.
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="panel">
      <div class="p-badge">Host access</div>
      <div class="p-title">SSH hardening and key lifecycle</div>
      <div class="p-body">
        Access uses key-based authentication only. Root login over SSH is disabled.
        <code style="color:var(--amber)">AllowUsers</code> (or equivalent match blocks)
        limits which accounts may connect. Mandatory SSH key rotation runs on a defined
        cadence. Private key material is stored in a vault, issued or rotated from there,
        and not copied by hand across hosts.
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="panel">
      <div class="p-badge">Administrative access</div>
      <div class="p-title">Bastion and private infrastructure</div>
      <div class="p-body">
        Access to internal servers is restricted through a bastion host. All infrastructure
        stays private and is not exposed on the public internet. Administrative paths go
        only through that entry point. The bastion sits behind VPN access and is
        monitored continuously for sign-in and session activity. It is the single
        controlled gateway for ops access to internal systems, instead of many
        direct SSH endpoints on the open network.
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>
